<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06109199 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06109199 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  MEDICAL; HEALTH; JUVENILE; BASEBALL  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Pushy parents are a bigger problem for a Little League pitcher than hisunderdeveloped arm, says a California orthopedic specialist who has treatedmajor league pitchers Tommy John and Orel Hershiser.;    &quot;I'm generally infavor of Little League,&quot; Dr. Frank Jobe said Wednesday after addressing theInternational Congress and Exposition on Sports Medicine and HumanPerformance. &quot;It serves a purpose in terms of getting along with your peers.It's a good teaching method for that.&quot;  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PUSHY PARENTS BANE TO PITCHERS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     A problem may arise, however, when the know-it-all parent tries to supplantthe coach, show his kid how it's really done and make him pitch too much inpractice.;    &quot;Pitching in Little League can be damaging to the shoulder andelbow,&quot; said Jobe, who works out of the Kerkan-Jobe Orthopedic Clinic inInglewood, Calif., and has treated members of the Los Angeles Dodgers.;    Toomuch throwing, not throwing itself, is the problem for kids of Little Leagueage, said Jobe.;    One result is Little League elbow, which occurs when thelittle bone on the outside of the elbow enlarges and becomes fragmented.;   But if players follow the rules that the Little League association has laidout regarding number of innings a child should pitch, number of pitches andamount of rest between games, then there should be no problems, he said.;   What about the curveball?;    &quot;I don't recommend it, but I don't think thecurve in itself is as bad as we (medical specialists) would have them believe.It doesn't show that way in our laboratory when we compare throwing straightto curve.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Vancouver, British Columbia  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAM